    'front_plate_raise',
    'Front Plate Raise',
    '{"merged_steps": ["The plate front raise is a variation of the dumbbell front raise where the lifter holds a weight plate between two hands, rather than using a dumbbell, barbell, or other weight.", "It can provide variety in a shoulder-focused muscle-building workout, or as part of an upper body or full-body circuit.", "1.", "While standing straight, hold a barbell plate in both hands at the 3 and 9 o''clock positions.", "Your palms should be facing each other and your arms should be extended and locked with a slight bend at the elbows and the plate should be down near your waist in front of you as far as you can go.", "**Tip**: The arms will remain in this position throughout the exercise.", "This will be your starting position.", "2.", "Slowly raise the plate as you exhale until it is a little above shoulder level.", "Hold the contraction for a second.", "As you inhale, slowly lower the plate back down to the starting position.", "3.", "Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions."], "sources": [{"source": "wger", "file": "C:\\Users\\kaiqu\\Desktop\\SOMMA\\datasets\\wger-master\\wger\\exercises\\fixtures\\exercise-base-data.json", "steps": ["The plate front raise is a variation of the dumbbell front raise where the lifter holds a weight plate between two hands, rather than using a dumbbell, barbell, or other weight.", "It can provide variety in a shoulder-focused muscle-building workout, or as part of an upper body or full-body circuit.", "1.", "While standing straight, hold a barbell plate in both hands at the 3 and 9 o''clock positions.", "Your palms should be facing each other and your arms should be extended and locked with a slight bend at the elbows and the plate should be down near your waist in front of you as far as you can go.", "**Tip**: The arms will remain in this position throughout the exercise.", "This will be your starting position.", "2.", "Slowly raise the plate as you exhale until it is a little above shoulder level.", "Hold the contraction for a second.", "As you inhale, slowly lower the plate back down to the starting position.", "3.", "Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions."], "description": "The plate front raise is a variation of the dumbbell front raise where the lifter holds a weight plate between two hands, rather than using a dumbbell, barbell, or other weight. It can provide variety in a shoulder-focused muscle-building workout, or as part of an upper body or full-body circuit. 1. While standing straight, hold a barbell plate in both hands at the 3 and 9 o''clock positions. Your palms should be facing each other and your arms should be extended and locked with a slight bend at the elbows and the plate should be down near your waist in front of you as far as you can go. **Tip**: The arms will remain in this position throughout the exercise. This will be your starting position. 2. Slowly raise the plate as you exhale until it is a little above shoulder level. Hold the contraction for a second. As you inhale, slowly lower the plate back down to the starting position. 3. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions."}], "summary": "The plate front raise is a variation of the dumbbell front raise where the lifter holds a weight plate between two hands, rather than using a dumbbell, barbell, or other weight. It can provide variety in a shoulder-focused muscle-building workout, or as part of an upper body or full-body circuit. 1. While standing straight, hold a barbell plate in both hands at the 3 and 9 o''clock positions. Your palms should be facing each other and your arms should be extended and locked with a slight bend at the elbows and the plate should be down near your waist in front of you as far as you can go. **Tip**: The arms will remain in this position throughout the exercise. This will be your starting position. 2. Slowly raise the plate as you exhale until it is a little above shoulder level. Hold the contraction for a second. As you inhale, slowly lower the plate back down to the starting position. 3. Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.", "setup": "The plate front raise is a variation of the dumbbell front raise where the lifter holds a weight plate between two hands, rather than using a dumbbell, barbell, or other weight.", "eccentric": "It can provide variety in a shoulder-focused muscle-building workout, or as part of an upper body or full-body circuit.", "concentric": "1. · While standing straight, hold a barbell plate in both hands at the 3 and 9 o''clock positions. · Your palms should be facing each other and your arms should be extended and locked with a slight bend at the elbows and the plate should be down near your waist in front of you as far as you can go. · **Tip**: The arms will remain in this position throughout the exercise. · This will be your starting position. · 2. · Slowly raise the plate as you exhale until it is a little above shoulder level. · Hold the contraction for a second. · As you inhale, slowly lower the plate back down to the starting position.", "regression": "3.", "safety": "Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions."}'::jsonb,
